rly twentieth centuries, they show how new definitions of modernity and welfare were developed and how new discourses and practices of inclusion and exclusion were contested and worked out. The contributors argue that colonial studies can no longer be confined to the units of analysis on which it once relied; instead of being the study of "the colonized," it must account for the shifting political terrain on which the very categories of colonized and colonizer have been shaped and patterned at different times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aColonies. 0aHistory, Modernx19th century. 0aHistory, Modernx20th century. 0aHistory, Moderny19th century. 0aHistory, Moderny20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryx19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryx20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCooper, Frederick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStoler, Ann Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520918085.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles